{"books":{"6":{"id":"1047","title":"Enchiridion of Augustine","description":"The Enchiridion, Manual, or Handbook of Augustine of Hippo is alternatively titled, \"Faith, Hope, and Love\". The Enchiridion is a compact treatise on Christian piety, written in response to a request by an otherwise unknown person, named Laurentis, shortly after the death of Saint Jerome in 420. It is intended as a model for Christian instruction or catechesis. - As the title indicates, the work is organized according to the three graces necessary for the Christian worship of God: Faith, Hope and Love. Under Faith, Augustine explains the use of the Apostles' Creed, in teaching Christian doctrine and in refuting heresies. Under Hope, he briefly explains the Lord's Prayer as a model of Christian prayer. The final part is a discourse on Christian love. (Summary from Wikipedia)<p>","url_text_source":"http:\/\/www.ccel.org\/fathers2\/NPNF1-03\/npnf1-03-23.htm#P2174_1095782","language":"English","copyright_year":"1883","num_sections":"7","url_rss":"http:\/\/librivox.org\/rss\/1047","url_zip_file":"http:\/\/www.archive.org\/download\/enchiridion_of_st_augustine_librivox\/enchiridion_of_st_augustine_librivox_64kb_mp3.zip","url_project":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Enchiridion_of_Augustine","url_librivox":"http:\/\/librivox.org\/the-enchiridion-by-saint-augustine\/","url_other":null,"totaltime":"2:59:49","totaltimesecs":10789,"authors":[{"id":"79","first_name":"Saint","last_name":"Augustine of Hippo","dob":"354","dod":"430"}],"url_iarchive":"http:\/\/www.archive.org\/details\/enchiridion_of_st_augustine_librivox","sections":[{"id":"137721","section_number":"1","title":"Chapters 1-17","listen_url":"http:\/\/www.logoslibrary.org\/librivox\/enchiridion_01_augustine.mp3","language":"English","playtime":"1558","file_name":null,"readers":[{"reader_id":"1324","display_name":"Darren L. Slider"}]},{"id":"137722","section_number":"2","title":"Chapters 18-33","listen_url":"http:\/\/www.logoslibrary.org\